England":"Sydenham, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wincanton, Somerset, England":"Wincanton, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England":"Sleaford, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1354–about 1400":"about 1354–about 1400","1349–1411":"1349–1411","1349–1412":"1349–1412","1354–1400":"1354–1400","1359–1396":"1359–1396","1354–1386":"1354–1386","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1330–1411":"1330–1411","1385":"1385","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1361":"1361","1327":"1327","1349":"1349","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1412":"1412","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1354":"1354","1386":"1386","about 1400":"about 1400","about 1354":"about 1354","about 1386":"about 1386","Holbrook Hall, Holbrook, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Sydenham, Somerset, England":"Sydenham, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Wincanton, Somerset, England":"Wincanton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England":"Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hussey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a nickname for someone who habitually wore a distinctive pair of boots or gaiters, from Old French <i>hosed</i>, <i>hoset</i>, <i>housé</i>, Middle English <i>hosey</i>, <i>hus(s)y</i>,‘booted, gaitered’ (from Latin <i>hosatus</i>).","English: status name or nickname from Middle English <i>hus(e)wyf</i> ‘mistress of a family; wife of a householder’ (a compound of Old English <i>hūs</i> ‘house’ + <i>wīf</i> ‘woman’). Though originally a woman's name, it is often found as a male surname, presumably in a derogatory sense. The vocabulary word became <i>hussie</i>, with the meaning ‘disreputable woman’, in the 16th century; the surname, however, is not associated with this meaning.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’. This was the name of a bardic family associated with the Maguires of Fermanagh, also Anglicized as   Oswell   or   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hosea","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  . Similarity with the Old Testament prophet's name Hosea (see 3 below) is accidental.","English: in Scotland, where the name is more common, it is sometimes a variant of   Hosie  , itself a form of   Hussey  , or else a variant of   Hossack  .","African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania): from the Biblical personal name <i>Hosea</i>. In the Old Testament, Hosea was a prophet who married a prostitute in order to illustrate Israel's unfaithfulness to God."]},{"name":"Hosie","meanings":["Scottish (northeast Scotland): variant of Irish   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Hassey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Oswell","meanings":["English: variant of   Oswald  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’ (see   Hussey  )."]},{"name":"Hosey","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Hussey was born about 1354, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Edmund Hussey, was 28 and his mother, Lady Joanna Whitton, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Joanna Hungerford. He died about 1400, in Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 48."},"et":{"about 1354–about 1400":"umbes 1354–umbes 1400","1349–1411":"1349–1411","1349–1412":"1349–1412","1354–1400":"1354–1400","1359–1396":"1359–1396","1354–1386":"1354–1386","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1330–1411":"1330–1411","1385":"1385","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1361":"1361","1327":"1327","1349":"1349","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1412":"1412","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1354":"1354","1386":"1386","about 1400":"umbes 1400","about 1354":"umbes 1354","about 1386":"umbes 1386","Holbrook Hall, Holbrook, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Sydenham, Somerset, England":"Sydenham, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wincanton, Somerset, England":"Wincanton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England":"Sleaford, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1354–about 1400":"noin 1354–noin 1400","1349–1411":"1349–1411","1349–1412":"1349–1412","1354–1400":"1354–1400","1359–1396":"1359–1396","1354–1386":"1354–1386","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1330–1411":"1330–1411","1385":"1385","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1361":"1361","1327":"1327","1349":"1349","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1412":"1412","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1354":"1354","1386":"1386","about 1400":"noin 1400","about 1354":"noin 1354","about 1386":"noin 1386","Holbrook Hall, Holbrook, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Sydenham, Somerset, England":"Sydenham,